System Requirements

    Operating Systems:

    • Linux 2.4.20 kernel
    • VxWorks Tornado 2.1(END)

    Hardware:

    • BCM94710-R4, BCM94710/4702-0D, BCM94710-AP(R4D2), BCM94704agr, BCM94704mpcb, BCM94712AGR, BCM94712LGR or BCM95350RG or BCM95351RG or BCM95352RG Base Reference Design -or-
    • Base Reference Design with a BCM94318E or BCM94318  MiniPCI card -or-
    • Base Reference Design with a BCM94306 MiniPCI card -or-
    • Base Reference Design with a BCM94309 MiniPCI card -or-
    • Base Reference Design with a BCM94318MPG/BCM94318MPAGH MiniPCI card -or-
    • Vendor Equivalent

Customer understands and acknowledges that the software is subject to all pertinent import and export laws of the United States.
    • Linux: In the new multi-SSID  functionality, the linux router only supports port-forwarding for the main SSID.
    • Linux: Application triggered port forwarding should only be disabled while traffic is not currently running.
    • Linux: Afterburner mode does not support fragmentation. Customer  web pages will need to ensure that this combination is not set. The Broadcom sample web pages does not currently do this.

    What's New in Release 3.130.35.0?

      • Linux and VxWorks: Added Range Expander under URE mode.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Added auto reconnect capability in URE to connect to an upstream AP in both Range Expander and Travel Router modes
      • Linux and VxWorks: Initial support for BCM94704MPCB 
      • Linux and VxWorks: Initial UAPSD WMM support 
      • Linux and VxWorks: Augmented the nvram flash update code, to prevent nvram corruption causing the device to potentially lock up as a result of power cycling in the middle of a flash write.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support to enable non-Broadcom client STAs to view and connect to the router with multiSSID enabled.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Fixed a regression where the auto channel selection stopped working.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Fixed a bug where restoring to factory defaults was not cleaning up additional NVRAM variables after using SES for WDS.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Fixed a bug where the reported RSSI was incorrect causing unnecessary roam scans.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Fixed a crash which sometimes occurred when Afterburner was enabled with WDS
      • Linux and VxWorks: Implemented DHCP relay in WET mode. The dhcp_relay NVRAM variable is used to turn this mode on or off (default off).

    What's New in Release 3.130.25.0?

      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support for BCM95351 
      • Linux and VxWorks: Updated PA parameter values for the BCM94712LGR rev 1.3 reference board
      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support for manual power control on the BCM4318 for manufacturing tests.

    What's New in Release 3.130.20.0?

      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support for 802.11h and 802.11d 
      • Linux: Added Secure Easy Setup for WDS.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Added functionality to support multiple SSIDs (multiple virtual wireles interfaces) from each physical wireless interface.
      • Linux and VxWorks: Added functionality to support a Travel Router mode, where one virtual wireless interface acts as a Station to an upstream Access Point and another virtual wireless interface acts as an Access Point serving multiple downstream Stations. Traffic will be routed between the two virtual wireless interfaces. 
      • Linux and VxWorks: Fixed a bug with PEAP authentication with a Windows 2000 server.
      • Linux: Upgraded to a newer tool chain (version 3.2.3.2). This fixes a problem with the logging daemon dying over time.

    What's New in Release 3.130.1.10?

      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support for new Japanese locales 
      • Linux and VxWorks: Fixed an issue where excessive false RADAR signals were detected when traffic was present on adjacent channels.

    What's New in Release 3.130.1.4?

      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support for 802.11h and 802.11d 
      • Linux: Added Secure Easy Setup for WDS.

    What's New in Release 3.110.6.0?

      • VxWorks: Supports for WPA2 added in this release
      • VxWorks: Support for WMM aded in this release
      • Linux and VxWorks: WET devices support WPA2 
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added feature to support saving/restoring NVRAM environment variables from the web UI
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for Afterburner over WDS. The entire ESS is modal with respect to Afterburner. 
      • Linux & VxWorks: Improved the Afterburner rate selection algorithm
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added Secure Easy Support  support for WET devices
      • Linux: Fixed a bug where the DHCP would under some conditions give the old subnet based IP address
      • Linux & VxWorks: When AES based stations exceed that what the hardware can support, the excess stations were not being handled by software earlier. Support has been added to support handling such clients in software.
      • Linux & VxWorks: The crypto library has been renamed to libbcmcrypto
      • Linux& VxWorks: Provided support for an external Broadcom wireless MAC without sprom. This enables wireless on the motherboard designs.
      • Linux& VxWorks: Supports for an open window in SES without disassociating the existing clients
      • VxWorks: A VxWorks big endian based Access Point  was not sending out packets on time in response to a PS Poll when the station was in power save.

    What's New in Release 3.90.39.0?

      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for the BCM95352 platform
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for BCM94318
      • Linux & VxWorks: The earlier release with AfterBurner enabled prevented enabling WDS. This has been fixed. The current implementation causes AfterBurner to be disabled when WDS is enabled
      • Linux & VxWorks: Channel 165 in the 802.11a band has been enabled based on updated specification
      • Linux & VxWorks: Fixed WMM priority not working on platforms with a builtin switch or with the 5325E
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for ST flash in page mode
      • Linux & VxWorks: Renamed the libcrypto library to libbcmcrypto
      • Linux: Fixed a bug in the Open router build that had some of the crypto libraries missing

    What's New in Release 3.90.7.0?

      • VxWorks: Added support for a VxWorks BSP. Support for a VLAN driver is also included that supports both tagged and untagged VLAN packets. Support has been added for both the BigEndian as well as LittleEndian versions.
      • Linux: Added support for WPA2 
      • Linux and VxWorks: Added support for WMM
      • Linux and VxWorks: Supports multiple wireless interfaces in both operating systems
      • Linux and VxWorks: Initial support for DualBand 4318MPAGH reference designs
      • Linux: Provided additional componentization to build smaller sized routers

    What's New in Release 3.80.13.0?

      • Linux: Added a mechanism to obtain WDS link status.
      • Linux: Added  web page item 'LAN/Default Gateway' to support setting up a default gateway when configured as an Access Point.
      • Linux: Added support for a DHCP client when configured as an Access Point. Previously the Access Point's IP was statically configured
      • Linux: Fixed a bug where the router was accepting association requests from clients having an invalid MAC address. This would cause the router to get confused at times
      • Linux: Added a new IOVAR IOCTL to control the numbers of clients that are alowed to associate to the AP.
      • Linux: Added statistics to get the time in seconds since a client station was associated.
      • Linux: Added a bit in the Broadcom Information Element to indicate if the router has been configured as a WDS.
      • Linux: Performing a WLC_SCAN_RESULTS after a WLC_SCAN will now return a null list till the scan completes. Previously it used to return the result of the previous scan. 
      • Linux: Improved the accuracy of the reported G-PHY CCK RSSI.
      • Linux: Changed the format of the NVRAM for some wireless security variables.

        Old: wl<N>_auth_mode=open
        New: wl<N>_auth=0 and wl<N>_auth_mode=none

        Old: wl<N>_auth_mode=shared 
        New: wl<N>_auth=1 and wl<N>_auth_mode=none

        Old: wl<N>_auth_mode=wpa
        New: wl<N>_auth=0 wl<N>_akm=wpa and wl<N>_auth_mode=none

        Old: wl<N>_auth_mode=psk
        New:  wl<N>_auth=0 wl<N>_akm=psk and wl<N>_auth_mode=none
      • Linux: Added the ability for syslog logging into a circular RAM buffer. The log mesages can be displayed on the "internal" web page. This feature is not compiled in by default. BB_FEATURE_IPC_SYSLOG in the busybox configuration and CONFIG_SYSV_FS in the kernel configuration need to be enabled to get this feature.

    What's New in Release 3.61.9.1?

      • Linux: Added support for multiple clients connected to the Broadcom WET device.

    What's New in Release 3.61.9.0?

      • Linux: Fixed a bug where the Broadcom web page was applying some of the 802.11g parameters when changing the dual band wireless to 802.11a mode.
      • Linux: Adds support for EZ 54g

    What's New in Release 3.61.5.0?

      • Boot Loader: CFE adds support for downloading images greater than 4M Bytes. CFE also adds support for  flash chip greater than 4MBytes.
      • Boot Loader: CFE's nvErase command syntax changed to
        nvErase <offset> <size>.
      • Boot Loader: The PMON cp2fl syntax changed to 
        cp2fl <src> <offset> <size>, where
        <offset> is 0 for PMON and
        <offset> is 40000 for linux.trx.
      • Linux: Upgraded to a newer tool chain (version 3.2.3)
      • Linux: WDS now supports WPA/PSK. The Broadcom reference web interface has the security method for the WDS link follow what the normal wireless AP is configured for.  However, the new functionality allows independent settings. Additionally, support is added to allow specifying which node in the WDS link is to act as the supplicant and which as the authenticator. The earlier mode of automatically determining this based on MAC address is also supported.
      • Linux: Added a new security mode that simultaneously supports AES, TKIP and legacy WEP stations.
      • Linux: Added support for WPA/PSK in WET mode.
      • Linux: Added support for 128 pairwise keys. The BCM94306 and BCM94309 B0 versions will support 12 hardware keys, while the C0 will support 50. The remaining clients will use software encryption. Software encryption is only supported for TKIP stations.
      • Linux: Afterburner adds support for 802.11a in addition to 802.11g. It now works for DualBand 4309 designs. Afterburner also extends supports for WPA-PSK including WEP, TKIP, and AES.
      • Linux: Fixed a bug in WPA/PSK mode where a 32 byte passphrase would fail.
      • Linux: Added "Authenticated Stations" table in wireless page which lists all currently authenticated station MAC addresses along with their status if they are associated and are WPA authorized.
      • Linux: Support for 5GHz High Band Channels (Channel 149, 153, 157, 161) on 4309-C0 board designs.
      • Linux: Fixed a multicast performance issue on the BCM94306/MCN94309 C0 cards.
      • Linux: Fixed a bug where when changing the country code of the locale in the wireless page other parameters that were changed on the page will change back to the original value.

    What's New in Release 3.51.21.6?

      • Linux: Adds support for Afterburner. There is a new board flag used to indicate Afterburner capability.  The wireless web page will indicate an Afterburner GMode if the hardware is capable of supporting this mode.

    What's New in Release 3.51.21.0?

      • Linux: Adds support for the BCM94712AGR.
      • Linux: Supports an external ADMTech 6996 VLAN chip on the ethernet interface.
      • Linux: Fixed GPIO allocation to be programmable instead of hardcoded.
      • Linux: Fixed a WET mode problem that prevented two WET devices connected to the same Access Point from talking to one another.
      • Boot Loader: Support for dynamic memory calibration at boot time on the BCM4704 and BCM4712.
      • Boot Loader: Support for a self decompressing CFE boot loader. This allows for a boot loader that fits within 128K currently.

    What's New in Release 3.41.21.0?

      • Linux: Supports multiple WAN interfaces over multiple PHYs. Multiple PPPoE interfaces can be created over a single PHY. 
      • Linux: Added support for USB gadget device to provide embedded USB device support.
      • Linux: Optimized performance on the BCM94702 based boards when enabling XPress Technology.
      • Linux: Optimized the router for better performance when handling clients that are in power save mode.
      • Linux: Optimized TKIP performance.
      • Linux: Support for Dualband C0 Reference Designs. 3.30.15 Supported C0 single band designs.
      • Linux: Re-vamped locales in favor of countries. Locales have been moved to an internal driver concept. It will be much easier for end users to use the country they are in. Old SPROM settings for default "locale" will still be honored. Over time, external configuration of locales will go away. Selection via an actual country name has a better fit for 802.11h as well as Windows own internal tracking of location.
      • Linux: Augmented the auto channel selection algorithm to dynamically choose the best channel when no clients are associated to it.
      • Linux: The router now reports the up-time on the status page.
      • Linux: Added the '54g Only' rate to the hidden internal page for WECA 802.11g testing.
      • Linux: Fixed a rare case where changing the interface on the WAN side from a Static IP / DHCP to PPPoE on the same network required rebooting the router for the packets to go out on the PPPoE connection.
      • Boot Loader: Fixed the legacy boot loader- PMON - to enable it to download images greater than 3M
      • Boot Loader: Added support for the AMD Mirro-Bit 2M and 4M flashes

    What's New in Release 3.31.12.0?

      • Linux: Support for the 4306C0 chip.
      • Linux: Fixed a bug which prevented a client using WPA from roaming from one AP to another. This bug would have only be seen with a newer version of Microsoft's supplicant. 
      • Linux: Support for the 4704 AGR router.
      • Linux: Enabled options to turn on the XPress Technology feature to all 802.11 network nodes. A UI element in the "Wireless" page controls this setting. 

    What's New in Release 3.31.3.0?

      • Linux: Upgraded the kernel to 2.4.20.
      • Linux: Substantial optimization of code to reduce the size of the combined flash content to less than 2 Mbytes
      • Linux: Augmented the application triggered port forwarding functionality to accept a range of port values as a trigger to open up the inbound ports.
      • Linux: Added support for multiple PPTP sessions.
      • Linux: Added support for Intel C3 flash.

    What's New in Release 3.21.12.0?

      • Linux: Fixed an inter-operability bug in WPA that prevented non-Broadcom stations from connecting to the Broadcom AP.

    What's New in Release 3.21.9.0?

      • Linux: Fixed a bug where the firmware would fail on systems without an UART.
      • Linux: Fixed a boot loader bug where it was resetting the NVRAM variables on the BCM94704agr while booting up.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Fixed 4301+2050 radio bug, preventing proper throughput to occur on the card.

    What's New in Release 3.21.7.0?

      • Linux: Added WPA support. This release supports TKIP, AES (4306/4309 Only), WPA, WPA-PSK as well as 802.1x authenticated WPA networks.
      • Linux: Security features can be independently controlled for each wireless interface.
      • Linux: The router can support for AES and TKIP encryption simultaneously, allowing client stations using AES or TKIP to connect. 
      • Linux: The router was validated to run on 8M of RAM.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for SST and MX flash.
      • Linux: Added support to automatically select the optimal channel when starting up. 
      • Linux: Added support for the BCM94704agr. Also support resetting to factory defaults when holding down the reset button longer than 5 seconds.
      • Linux: Added support for the connect on demand and service name features when using PPPoE.
      • Linux: The web pages now accept MAC addresses in either a ':' or '-' seperated format.
      • Linux: The router is now certifiable for the UPnP logo.
      • Linux: Added support for an 802.11b-only mode when using a BCM94306 card running on a 802.11g band.
      • Linux: Added  support for NVRAM variables greater than 256 bytes.
      • Linux: Fixed a bug in the web page when operating in the 802.11a band, where the selectable rates only went up to 36Mbps
      • VxWorks: Fixed a bug where large packets (>1500 bytes) was not handled correctly.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for 4301+2050 reference design

     What's New in Release 3.11.48.0?

      • Linux: Support for multiple wireless MiniPCI cards in the router. Support includes independent WEP, SSID, bridging mode, locale, network type, radio control, MAC restrictions modes etc.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Support for 802.11a only MiniPCI card as well as dual band 802.11a/b/g MiniPCI cards in the router.  The router dynamically displays the choice of bands available to select from based on the type of wireless card(s) plugged in.

      • Linux & VxWorks: Changed the GUI in the "Filters" page. The router now supports a unified "LAN Client Filters" interface instead of separate interfaces for "LAN IP Filters", "LAN TCP Port Filters" and "LAN UDP Port Filters". Additionally, support for time based filtering has also been added.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Changed the GUI in the "Routing" page. The router now supports a unified "Port Forwards" interface instead of separate "LAN TCP Port Forwards" and "LAN UDP Port Forwards".
      • Linux & VxWorks: Implemented "Application Specific Port Forwarding" to allow an application to trigger the opening of ports to the outside. This prevents the need to permanently open ports to the outside using the "Port Forwards" menu. Additionally, the LAN IP address to map the open ports to is determined dynamically (based on where the application is running). 
      • Linux : Added support for Application Level Gateways (ALG) for TFTP and H323.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Support of up to 3 NTP servers, with initial default servers in place.
      • Linux & VxWorks: UPnP and the web pages now agree with port mappings created using either interface
      • Linux & VxWorks: Fixed a bug in the AP that was causing association to take much longer when there was significantly large amount of wireless traffic present. 
      • Linux & VxWorks: Throughput and consistency of throughput improvements.
      • Linux & VxWorks: In client driver releases prior to 3.10.39.0, when an AP in a BSS network enables g-protection via Info Element 47, throughput will be very low. Connectivity is still enabled so that a user may upgrade to a later driver.
      • Linux: Added a LAN lease time GUI element
      • Linux: Fixed a bug where changing the "Bridge Restrict" mode, from enabled to disabled (or the other way around), during an established WDS session would cause WDS bridging to fail.
      • Linux: Full WECA tests executed at BRCM

     What's New in Release 3.11.9.0?

      • Linux & VxWorks: Added Dynamic 11g configuration in the web pages
        • 802.11b-Only mode turns of 11g network capabilities and runs in full 802.11b compatible mode
        • 54G-Auto (default) mode dynamically moves from short to long slot based on presence of 11b nets
        • 54G-Only is the same as 54G-Auto, but will not allow 11b STA's to associate, and will still fall back into long slot in the presence of 11b nets.
        • BRCM-54G-Only is hard coded for short slot, will not fall back to long slot in the presence of 11b nets. This mode should only be used under controlled environments as it will out-compete long slot networks.
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support for independent multicast rate
      • Linux & VxWorks: Power save mode has been fixed for 11g networks
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added support to properly age STA's so networks can bump back up to short slot mode
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added a new IOCTL to return a list of associated STA's MAC addresses
      • Linux & VxWorks: Added interface control for 11g nonERP indication element such that 11g STA's can be forced to use RTS/CTS
      • Linux & VxWorks: Performance stability attained with rate selection algorithm tuned for CCK and OFDM ratesets
